06168nam a22006975i 9780824837600DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20092009hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248376007 a10.1515/97808248376002doi  a(DE-B1597)484151  a(OCoLC)1013957972  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aREL0300002bisacsh04a280/.4095195222/eng1 aLee, Timothy S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBorn Again :bEvangelicalism in Korea /cTimothy S. Lee. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Breakthrough for a New Moral Order, 1885–1919 -- tChapter 2. Conflict, Introversion, and a Tradition of Korean Revivalists, 1920–1953 -- tChapter 3. Evangelicalism Takes Off in South Korea, 1953–1988 -- tChapter 4. The Intensely Practical and Devotional Character of Korean Evangelicalism -- tEpilogue. The Beleaguered Success of Korean Evangelicalism in The 1990S -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aKnown as Asia’s "evangelical superpower," South Korea today has some of the largest and most dynamic churches in the world and is second only to the United States in the number of missionaries it dispatches abroad. Understanding its evangelicalism is crucial to grasping the course of its modernization, the rise of nationalism and anticommunism, and the relationship between Christians and other religionists within the country. Born Again is the first book in a Western language to consider the introduction, development, and character of evangelicalism in Korea—from its humble beginnings at the end of the nineteenth century to claiming one out of every five South Koreans as an adherent at the end of the twentieth. In this thoughtful and thorough study, Timothy S. Lee argues that the phenomenal rise of this particular species of Christianity can be attributed to several factors. As a religion of salvation, evangelicalism appealed powerfully to multitudes of Koreans, arriving at a time when the country was engulfed in unprecedented crises that discredited established social structures and traditional attitudes. Evangelicalism attracted and empowered Koreans by offering them a more compelling worldview and a more meaningful basis for association. Another factor is evangelicalisms positive connection to Korean nationalism and South Korean anticommunism. It shared in the aspirations and hardships of Koreans during the Japanese occupation and was legitimated again during and after the Korean conflict as South Koreans experienced the trauma of the war. Equally important was evangelicals’ relentless proselytization efforts throughout the twentieth century.Lee explores the beliefs and practices that have become the hallmarks of Korean evangelicalism: kibok (this-worldly blessing), saebyok kido (daybreak prayer), and kumsik kido (fasting prayer). He concludes that Korean evangelicalism is distinguishable from other forms of evangelicalism by its intensely practical and devotional bent. He reveals how, after a long period of impressive expansion, including the mammoth campaigns of the 1970s and 1980s that drew millions to its revivals, the 1990s was a decade of ambiguity for the faith. On the one hand, it had become South Korea’s most influential religion, affecting politics, the economy, and civil society. On the other, it found itself beleaguered by a stalemate in growth, the shortcomings of its leaders, and conflicts with other religions. Evangelicalism had not only risen in South Korean society; it had also, for better or worse, become part of the establishment.Despite this significance, Korean evangelicalism has not received adequate treatment from scholars outside Korea. Born Again will therefore find an eager audience among English-speaking historians of modern Korea, scholars of comparative religion and world Christianity, and practitioners of the faith.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aEvangelicalismzKorea (South)xHistory. 0aProtestantismzKorea (South). 7aRELIGION / Christian Ministry / Evangelism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082483760040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824837600423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824837600.jpg  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066325-9  University of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK